rylands are right here, in our midst.', 2065, 0), (268933, 'She was certain this trip would be a landslide of regret, anger and resentment, crumbling around a day of sadness.', 46158, 0), (268934, 'Her hands moved up his arms and tried to ignore the tingling zapping her skin like the metal edges of the Operation game.', 46158, 0), (268935, 'The treasures of life are hidden in a book.', 2878, 0), (268936, 'But books, when you want to buy them, are costly and, when you need to sell them, valueless.', 46159, 0), (268937, 'After three years of English at Cambridge, being force-fed literary theory, I was almost convinced that literature was all coded messages about Marxism and the death of the self. I crawled out of the post-structuralist desert thirsty for heroines I could cry and laugh with. I was jaded. I craved trash.', 46160, 0), (268938, 'He returned my smile with a half grin. "So what do you blog about? Knitting? Puzzles? Being lonely?', 366, 0), (268939, 'It''s a strange sensation to pick up a book you read and enjoyed just a few months ago and discover you don''t remember it.', 1286, 0), (268940, 'The uninitiated might say that I am lost in my books, but I know I am more found than lost.', 11479, 0), (268941, 'Writing a book is like raising a child. They are conceived in private, and with hard labor, delivered in due time and given a name. Our own DNA is written all over them, and we pray their life will be a blessing to others.', 39508, 0), (268942, 'Someone mentioned therapy to me once. I read a book instead. ~ Drew Stirling', 26755, 0), (268943, 'Nothing worth doing is ever easy.', 46161, 0), (268944, 'Life is a book. When one chapter ends, the next one begins...', 34195, 0), (268945, 'Everything I try to hide ends up screaming from a mountaintop.', 8495, 0), (268946, 'To love a book is, above all, to love its author: we want to meet him again, we want to spend our days with him.', 1261, 0), (268947, 'The wheel… is an extension of the foot. The book… is an ex